1Ô∏è‚É£ Biggest Challenge You Faced

S ‚Äì Situation:
During the booking module, multiple users tried to book the same room at the same time, leading to double bookings.

T ‚Äì Task:
I needed to ensure that two users could not book the same room for overlapping dates.

A ‚Äì Action:
I implemented synchronized blocks in the booking service and later used optimistic and pessimistic locking in JPA to handle concurrent access at the database level.

R ‚Äì Result:
The issue of double booking was completely resolved, ensuring data consistency even under high load.
Keywords: concurrency, data integrity, transaction safety.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Mistake or Failure

S ‚Äì Situation:
Initially, I wrote a single large query to fetch hotel and room details using multiple joins to reduce database calls.

T ‚Äì Task:
The goal was to optimize performance, but it caused N+1 query problems and high response time.

A ‚Äì Action:
I investigated and learned about lazy vs eager loading, and then used fetch joins and EntityGraph to optimize data fetching.

R ‚Äì Result:
Performance improved significantly, and I learned to analyze and optimize queries early in development.
Lesson: Don‚Äôt assume; measure and validate performance.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Leadership Example

S ‚Äì Situation:
During the integration of the payment module, our team faced issues synchronizing payment confirmation with booking status.

T ‚Äì Task:
We needed a reliable flow where the booking would be confirmed only after successful payment.

A ‚Äì Action:
I proposed and implemented an event-driven solution, where the booking service updates status only upon receiving a confirmation event from the payment service.
I also documented and explained the flow to the team.

R ‚Äì Result:
The system became more reliable, booking mismatches were eliminated, and my initiative improved team collaboration.
Leadership Highlight: Guided team with technical and communication clarity.
4Ô∏è‚É£ Conflict Resolution (Feign vs WebClient)

S ‚Äì Situation:
Our team debated whether to use RestTemplate, WebClient, or Feign Client for microservice communication.

T ‚Äì Task:
As the developer integrating booking and payment services, I needed to help finalize the best approach for scalability and maintainability.

A ‚Äì Action:
I compared all three approaches and presented my analysis:

RestTemplate ‚Üí simple but blocking

WebClient ‚Üí non-blocking and reactive

Feign Client ‚Üí declarative and ideal for Spring Cloud microservices
I recommended using Feign Client for internal service calls and WebClient in the gateway for async calls.

R ‚Äì Result:
The team agreed, and communication between services became cleaner and more efficient.
Skill: Technical decision-making and collaboration.
